ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-11 According to the FAA inspector, the airplane sustained substantial damage. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-7 The local flight originated from the David Wayne Hooks Memorial Airport, Houston, Texas, at 1156. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-4 The airplane was registered to Southwestern Gas Pipeline Inc., of The Woodlands, Texas, and operated by the pilot. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-5 The airline transport pilot, sole occupant of the airplane, sustained serious injuries. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-3 On June 23, 2001, at 1158 central daylight time, a Cessna 182Q, N4834N, was substantially damaged when it impacted terrain following a loss of engine power during the initial takeoff climb near Houston, Texas. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-6 Visual meteorological conditions prevailed and a flight plan was not filed for the 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 maintenance test flight. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-1 This is preliminary information, subject to change, and may contain errors. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-2 Any errors in this report will be corrected when the final report has been completed. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-10 Subsequently, the airplane impacted ground. 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-8 According to witnesses, the airplane departed from runway 17L and was climbing through 300 feet when the engine "failed." 
ntsb4086txt-1-5-5-0-9 The airplane was seen making a "steep," 180-degree turn to the right, back toward the airport, when the right wing dropped and the nose entered a nose low attitude. 
